---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Services"
  description="Professional proofreading and editorial services by Lynden Howells — catching errors spellcheckers miss, improving clarity, and ensuring your documents are ready to publish."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Services</h1>
      <p class="page-header__sub">Proofreading and editorial services, delivered with precision</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Proofreading</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Spellcheckers and grammar checkers are useful tools — but they are not proofreaders.
        They will not catch a word that is spelled correctly but used in the wrong context.
        They will not flag that your document was composed with American English settings
        when your audience expects Australian spelling. They will not notice that "public"
        became something else entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        What I provide is a trained human eye that has been doing this — full-time — for over
        35 years. I review for:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spelling (including Australian vs. American English consistency)</li>
        <li>Grammar and punctuation</li>
        <li>Word usage and contextual accuracy</li>
        <li>Consistency of style, formatting, and terminology throughout</li>
        <li>Typographical errors and layout anomalies</li>
        <li>Numbering, headings, and cross-references</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Editorial Services</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Sometimes a document is error-free but still doesn't read as well as it could.
        Beyond catching mistakes, I can offer suggestions for clearer, sharper phrasing.
      </p>
      <p>
        A classic example of why this matters: a classified ad once read, <em>"Piano wanted
        for a lady with ivory legs."</em> Technically correct in spelling — but clearly
        not what the writer intended.
      </p>
      <p>
        Editorial suggestions are always presented as options, not impositions. You retain
        full control over your document. My role is to give you the information you need
        to make it the best it can be.
      </p>

      <h2>How I work</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        I work with clients in person in Hobart and remotely by phone, fax, or email —
        which means I can assist clients anywhere in Australia. Most projects are handled
        entirely electronically for speed and convenience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before accepting a job I ask to see a sample of the work. This allows me to give
        you an accurate quote and ensure I can deliver within your timeframe. I won't
        quote sight unseen — and you wouldn't want me to.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p style="margin:0;">
          Typical turnaround for a 20-page A4 document is <strong>24–48 hours</strong>.
          Urgent work is available at a pre-negotiated rate.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-2"><a href="/rates" class="btn" style="margin-right:1rem;">Rates &amp; Turnaround</a><a href="/contact" class="btn">Get a Quote</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
